<p>
<seg id=1> The UN Economic Commission for Latin America and the Caribbeans said that economic growth in that area will decrease by 1% next year. </seg>
<seg id=2> And the situation might be even worse, according to the commission. </seg>
<seg id=3> Mick, correspondent of VOA South American Department will have the details. Presented by Tianye. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> According to the initial analysis of the UN Economic Commission, economic growth in Latin American and the Caribbeans this year will be 2.3%, which suffers a sharp decrease from 5.2% last year. </seg>
<seg id=5> The figure will be much lower without a strong economic growth in the first half-year. </seg>
<seg id=6> Despite the economic instability outside Latin America and the Caribbean, Economy in this area grows relatively well. </seg>
<seg id=7> However, the economy has been badly influenced, which will continue till the year after. </seg>
<seg id=8> The hard economic situation in Brazil reflected in some countries of the south part of South America. </seg>
<seg id=9> Those countries were effected by the low prices of export products. </seg>
<seg id=10> According to the Commission, most countries chose to protect their currency by rising the interest rate. </seg>
<seg id=11> This kind of measure restrained the economic growth, leading to the rise of unemployment. </seg>
<seg id=12> "If those countries want to maintain their competitiveness in the grobal market through devaluation, they are taking the risk of high inflation," said the report. </seg>
</p>
